# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-catalog
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-catalog/data-catalog] A **database catalog** of a database instance consists of metadata in which definitions of database objects such as base tables, views (virtual tables), synonyms, value ranges, indexes, users, and user groups are stored.
[src:data-catalog/data-catalog] It is an architecture product that documents the database's content and data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-catalog] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the INFORMATION_SCHEMA, but not all databases follow this, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:data-catalog/data-catalog] For an example of database-specific metadata access methods, see Oracle metadata.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] A **data dictionary**, or metadata repository, as defined in the *IBM Dictionary of Computing*, is a "centralized repository of information about data such as meaning, relationships to other data, origin, usage, and format".
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] *Oracle* defines it as a collection of tables with metadata.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] The terms *data dictionary* and *data repository* indicate a more general software utility than a catalogue.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] A *catalogue* is closely coupled with the DBMS software.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] It provides the information stored in it to the user and the DBA, but it is mainly accessed by the various software modules of the DBMS itself, such as DDL and DML compilers, the query optimiser, the transaction processor, report generators, and the constraint enforcer.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] On the other hand, a *data dictionary* is a data structure that stores metadata, i.e., (structured) data about information.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] The software package for a stand-alone data dictionary or data repository may interact with the software modules of the DBMS, but it is mainly used by the designers, users and administrators of a computer system for information resource management.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] These systems maintain information on system hardware and software configuration, documentation, application and users as well as other information relevant to system administration.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] With an active data dictionary, the dictionary is updated first and changes occur in the DBMS automatically as a result.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Database users and application developers can benefit from an authoritative data dictionary document that catalogs the organization, contents, and conventions of one or more databases.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] This typically includes the names and descriptions of various tables (records or entities) and their contents (fields), plus additional details, like the type and length of each data element.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Another important piece of information that a data dictionary can provide is the relationship between tables.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] This is sometimes referred to in entity-relationship diagrams (ERDs), or if using set descriptors, identifying which sets database tables participate in.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] In an active data dictionary constraints may be placed upon the underlying data.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] For instance, a range may be imposed on the value of numeric data in a data element (field), or a record in a table may be forced to participate in a set relationship with another record-type.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Additionally, a distributed DBMS may have certain location specifics described within its active data dictionary (e.g. where tables are physically located).
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] The data dictionary consists of record types (tables) created in the database by systems generated command files, tailored for each supported back-end DBMS.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Oracle has a list of specific views for the "sys" user.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] This allows users to look up the exact information that is needed.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Command files contain SQL Statements for `CREATE TABLE`, `CREATE UNIQUE INDEX`, `ALTER TABLE` (for referential integrity), etc., using the specific statement required by that type of database.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] There is no universal standard as to the level of detail in such a document.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] In the construction of database applications, it can be useful to introduce an additional layer of data dictionary software, i.e. middleware, which communicates with the underlying DBMS data dictionary.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Such a "high-level" data dictionary may offer additional features and a degree of flexibility that goes beyond the limitations of the native "low-level" data dictionary, whose primary purpose is to support the basic functions of the DBMS, not the requirements of a typical application.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] For example, a high-level data dictionary can provide alternative entity-relationship models tailored to suit different applications that share a common database.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Extensions to the data dictionary also can assist in query optimization against distributed databases.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Additionally, DBA functions are often automated using restructuring tools that are tightly coupled to an active data dictionary.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Software frameworks aimed at rapid application development sometimes include high-level data dictionary facilities, which can substantially reduce the amount of programming required to build menus, forms, reports, and other components of a database application, including the database itself.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] For example, PHPLens includes a PHP class library to automate the creation of tables, indexes, and foreign key constraints portably for multiple databases.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Another PHP-based data dictionary, part of the RADICORE toolkit, automatically generates program objects, scripts, and SQL code for menus and forms with data validation and complex joins.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] For the ASP.NET environment, Base One's data dictionary provides cross-DBMS facilities for automated database creation, data validation, performance enhancement (caching and index utilization), application security, and extended data types.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Visual DataFlex features provides the ability to use DataDictionaries as class files to form middle layer between the user interface and the underlying database.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] The intent is to create standardized rules to maintain data integrity and enforce business rules throughout one or more related applications.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Some industries use generalized data dictionaries as technical standards to ensure interoperability between systems.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] The real estate industry, for example, abides by a RESO's Data Dictionary to which the National Association of REALTORS mandates its MLSs comply with through its policy handbook.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] This intermediate mapping layer for MLSs' native databases is supported by software companies which provide API services to MLS organizations.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Developers use a data description specification (DDS) to describe data attributes in file descriptions that are external to the application program that processes the data, in the context of an IBM i.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] The *sys.ts$* table in Oracle stores information about every table in the database.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] It is part of the data dictionary that is created when the Oracle Database is created.
[src:data-catalog/data-dictionary] Developers may also use DDS context from free and open-source software (FOSS) for structured and transactional queries in open environments.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Data governance involves delegating authority over data and exercising that authority through decision-making processes.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] It plays a role in enhancing the value of data assets.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Data governance at the macro level involves regulating cross-border data flows among countries, which is more precisely termed *international data governance*.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] There have been several international groups established by research organizations that aim to grant access to their data.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] These groups that enable an exchange of data are, as a result, exposed to domestic and international legal interpretations that ultimately decide how data is used.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] However, as of 2023, there are no international laws or agreements specifically focused on data protection.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Data governance is the set of principles, policies, and processes that guide the effective and responsible use of data within an organization.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] It creates a framework for decision making, accountability, and oversight across the data lifecycle, from creation and storage to sharing and disposal.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Data governance is closely linked with data management, which provides the practical methods to carry out governance objectives.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] These methods include data quality assurance, metadata management, master data management, security controls, and compliance monitoring.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Together, governance and management aim to maximize the value of data as a strategic asset, reduce risks from misuse or inaccuracy, and ensure compliance with regulatory, ethical, and business requirements.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] The importance of this discipline has grown with the rise of big data, cloud computing, and artificial intelligence, where consistent standards and stewardship are essential for privacy protection, interoperability, and informed decision making.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] In 2010, they published a data governance framework based on five components: data principles (which define the data's purpose by an organization), data quality, metadata, data access, and data lifecycle.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] In 2017, the ISO released a framework for data governance, ISO/IEC 38505-1:2017.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Due to the increased use of large language models and the datasets used to train them, a 2022 paper proposed a data governance framework in the context of human rights.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Other well-known data governance frameworks include ISO 8000, the CMMI Data Management Maturity (DMM) Model, and DAMA-DMBOK.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] While data governance initiatives can be driven by a desire to improve data quality, they are often driven by C-level leaders responding to external regulations.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] In a recent report conducted by the CIO WaterCooler community, 54% stated the key driver was efficiencies in processes; 39% - regulatory requirements; and only 7% customer service.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Examples of these regulations include Sarbanes–Oxley Act, Basel I, Basel II, HIPAA, GDPR, cGMP, and a number of data privacy regulations.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] To achieve compliance with these regulations, business processes and controls require formal management processes to govern the data subject to these regulations.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Successful programs identify drivers that are meaningful to both supervisory and executive leadership.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Common themes among the external regulations center on the need to manage risk.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] The risks can be financial misstatement, inadvertent release of sensitive data, or poor data quality for key decisions.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Methods to manage these risks vary from industry to industry.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Examples of commonly referenced best practices and guidelines include COBIT, ISO/IEC 38500, and others.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] The proliferation of regulations and standards creates challenges for data governance professionals, particularly when multiple regulations overlap the data being managed.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Organizations often launch data governance initiatives to address these challenges.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Data governance initiatives improve the quality of data by assigning a team responsible for data's accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, validity, and uniqueness.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] This team usually consists of executive leadership, project management, line-of-business managers, and data stewards.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] The team usually employs a methodology for tracking and improving enterprise data, such as Six Sigma, and tools for data mapping, profiling, cleansing, and monitoring data.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Many data governance initiatives are also inspired by past attempts to fix information quality at the departmental level, which can lead to incongruent and redundant data quality processes.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Most large companies have many applications and databases that can not easily share information.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Therefore, knowledge workers within large organizations may not have access to the data they need to best do their jobs.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] When they do have access to the data, the data quality may be poor.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] By setting up a data governance practice or corporate data authority (individual or area responsible for determining how to proceed, in the best interest of the business, when a data issue arises), these problems can be mitigated.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Implementation of a data governance initiative may vary in scope as well as origin.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Sometimes, an executive mandate will arise to initiate an enterprise-wide effort.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Sometimes the mandate will be to create a pilot project or projects, limited in scope and objectives, aimed at either resolving existing issues or demonstrating value.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Sometimes, an initiative originates from lower down in the organization's hierarchy and will be deployed in a limited scope to demonstrate value to potential sponsors higher up in the organization.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] The initial scope of an implementation can vary greatly as well, from review of a one-off IT system to a cross-organization initiative.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Leaders of successful data governance programs declared at the Data Governance Conference in Orlando, FL, in December 2006, that data governance is about 80 to 95 percent communication.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] That stated, it is a given that many of the objectives of a data governance program must be accomplished with appropriate tools.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Many vendors are now positioning their products as data governance tools.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Due to the different focus areas of various data governance initiatives, a given tool may or may not be appropriate.
[src:data-catalog/data-governance] Additionally, many tools that are not marketed as governance tools address governance needs and demands.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage facilitates the ability to replay specific segments or inputs of the dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This can be used in debugging or regenerating lost outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In database systems, this concept is closely related to data provenance, which involves maintaining records of inputs, entities, systems and processes that influence data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data provenance provides a historical record of data origins and transformations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage information includes technical metadata about data transformations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Enriched data lineage may include additional elements such as data quality test results, reference data, data models, business terminology, data stewardship information, program management details and enterprise systems associated with data points and transformations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage visualization tools often include masking features that allow users to focus on information relevant to specific use cases.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] To unify representations across disparate systems, metadata normalization or standardization may be required.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Representation broadly depends on the scope of the metadata management and reference point of interest.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage provides sources of the data and intermediate data flow hops from the reference point with **backward data lineage**, leading to the final destination's data points and its intermediate data flows with **forward data lineage**.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] These views can be combined with end-to-end **lineage** for a reference point that provides a complete audit trail of that data point of interest from sources to their final destinations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] As the data points or hops increase, the complexity of such representation becomes incomprehensible.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, the best feature of the data lineage view is the ability to simplify the view by temporarily masking unwanted peripheral data points.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Tools with the masking feature enable scalability of the view and enhance analysis with the best user experience for both technical and business users.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage also enables companies to trace sources of specific business data to track errors, implement changes in processes and implementing system migrations to save significant amounts of time and resources.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage can improve efficiency in business intelligence BI processes.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage can be represented visually to discover the data flow and movement from its source to destination via various changes and hops on its way in the enterprise environment.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This includes how the data is transformed along the way, how the representation and parameters change and how the data splits or converges after each hop.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A simple representation of the Data Lineage can be shown with dots and lines, where dots represent data containers for data points, and lines connecting them represent transformations the data undergoes between the data containers.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage can be visualized at various levels based on the granularity of the view.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] At a very high-level, data lineage is visualized as systems that the data interacts with before it reaches its destination.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] At its most granular, visualizations at the data point level can provide the details of the data point and its historical behavior, attribute properties and trends and data quality of the data passed through that specific data point in the data lineage.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The scope of the data lineage determines the volume of metadata required to represent its data lineage.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Usually, data governance and data management of an organization determine the scope of the data lineage based on their regulations, enterprise data management strategy, data impact, reporting attributes and critical data elements of the organization.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Distributed systems like Google Map Reduce, Microsoft Dryad, Apache Hadoop (an open-source project) and Google Pregel provide such platforms for businesses and users.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, even with these systems, Big Data analytics can take several hours, days or weeks to run, simply due to the data volumes involved.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] For example, a ratings prediction algorithm for the Netflix Prize challenge took nearly 20 hours to execute on 50 cores, and a large-scale image processing task to estimate geographic information took 3 days to complete using 400 cores.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] "The Large Synoptic Survey Telescope is expected to generate terabytes of data every night and eventually store more than 50 petabytes, while in the bioinformatics sector, the 12 largest genome sequencing houses in the world now store petabytes of data apiece.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] It is very difficult for a data scientist to trace an unknown or an unanticipated result.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Big data analytics is the process of examining large data sets to uncover hidden patterns, unknown correlations, market trends, customer preferences and other useful business information.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Machine learning, among other algorithms, is used to transform and analyze the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Due to the large size of the data, there could be unknown features in the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The massive scale and unstructured nature of data, the complexity of these analytics pipelines, and long runtimes pose significant manageability and debugging challenges.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Even a single error in these analytics can be extremely difficult to identify and remove.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] While one may debug them by re-running the entire analytics through a debugger for stepwise debugging, this can be expensive due to the amount of time and resources needed.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Auditing and data validation are other major problems due to the growing ease of access to relevant data sources for use in experiments, the sharing of data between scientific communities and use of third-party data in business enterprises.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] As such, more cost-efficient ways of analyzing data intensive scale-able computing (DISC) are crucial to their continued effective use.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] According to an EMC/IDC study, 2.8 ZB of data were created and replicated in 2012.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Furthermore, the same study states that the digital universe will double every two years between now and 2020, and that there will be approximately 5.2 TB of data for every person in 2020.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Based on current technology, the storage of this much data will mean greater energy usage by data centers.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Unstructured data usually refers to information that doesn't reside in a traditional row-column database.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Unstructured data files often include text and multimedia content, such as e-mail messages, word processing documents, videos, photos, audio files, presentations, web pages and many other kinds of business documents.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] While these types of files may have an internal structure, they are still considered "unstructured" because the data they contain doesn't fit neatly into a database.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The amount of unstructured data in enterprises is growing many times faster than structured databases are growing.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Big data can include both structured and unstructured data, but IDC estimates that 90 percent of Big Data is unstructured data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The fundamental challenge of unstructured data sources is that they are difficult for non-technical business users and data analysts alike to unbox, understand and prepare for analytic use.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Beyond issues of structure, the sheer volume of this type of data contributes to such difficulty.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Because of this, current data mining techniques often leave out valuable information and make analyzing unstructured data laborious and expensive.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In today's competitive business environment, companies have to find and analyze the relevant data they need quickly.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The challenge is going through the volumes of data and accessing the level of detail needed, all at a high speed.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The challenge only grows as the degree of granularity increases.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Some vendors are using increased memory and parallel processing to crunch large volumes of data quickly.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Another method is putting data in-memory but using a grid computing approach, where many machines are used to solve a problem.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Both approaches allow organizations to explore huge data volumes.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Even with this level of sophisticated hardware and software, a few of the image processing tasks in large scale take a few days to few weeks.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Debugging of the data processing is extremely hard due to long run times.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A third approach of advanced data discovery solutions combines self-service data prep with visual data discovery, enabling analysts to simultaneously prepare and visualize data side-by-side in an interactive analysis environment offered by newer companies, such as Trifacta, Alteryx and others.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Another method to track data lineage is spreadsheet programs such as Excel that offer users cell-level lineage, or the ability to see which cells are dependent on another.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, the structure of the transformation is lost.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Similarly, ETL or mapping software provide transform-level lineage, yet this view typically doesn't display data and is too coarse-grained to distinguish between transforms that are logically independent (e.g. transforms that operate on distinct columns) or dependent.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Big Data platforms have a very complicated structure, where data is distributed across a vast range.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Typically, the jobs are mapped into several machines and results are later combined by the reduce operations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Debugging a Big Data pipeline becomes very challenging due to the very nature of the system.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] It will not be an easy task for the data scientist to figure out which machine's data has outliers and unknown features causing a particular algorithm to give unexpected results.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data provenance or data lineage can be used to make the debugging of Big Data pipeline easier.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This necessitates the collection of data about data transformations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The below section will explain data provenance in more detail.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In information systems, **data provenance** is information about the entities, activities, and agents involved in producing a piece of data; it records how data was derived and can be used to assess quality, reliability, and trustworthiness.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Classical database research distinguishes **why**, **where**, and **how** provenance and shows how these forms support tasks such as query debugging, view maintenance, confidence estimation, and annotation propagation.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In scientific workflows, provenance documents the derivation history from original sources through workflow steps, supporting reproducibility and reuse of results.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Open, implementation-oriented specifications such as **OpenLineage** model lineage in terms of jobs, runs, and datasets to enable automated capture from modern data pipelines.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Provenance is information about entities, activities and people involved in producing a piece of data or thing, which can be used to form assessments about its quality, reliability or trustworthiness.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] is defined as a record that describes the people, institutions, entities and activities involved in producing, influencing, or delivering a piece of data or something.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In particular, the provenance of information is crucial in deciding whether information is to be trusted, how it should be integrated with other diverse information sources, and how to give credit to its originators when reusing it.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In an open and inclusive environment such as the Web, where users find information that is often contradictory or questionable, provenance can help those users to make trust judgements.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Intuitively, for an operator T producing output o , lineage consists of triplets of form $\{i,T,o\}$ , where i is the set of inputs to T used to derive o .
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A query that finds the inputs deriving an output is called a *backward tracing query*, while one that finds the outputs produced by an input is called a *forward tracing query*.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Backward tracing is useful for debugging, while forward tracing is useful for tracking error propagation.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Tracing queries also form the basis for replaying an original dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, to efficiently use lineage in a DISC system, we need to be able to capture lineage at multiple levels (or granularities) of operators and data, capture accurate lineage for DISC processing constructs and be able to trace through multiple dataflow stages efficiently.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A DISC system consists of several levels of operators and data, and different use cases of lineage can dictate the level at which lineage needs to be captured.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lineage can be captured at the level of the job, using files and giving lineage tuples of form {IF i, M RJob, OF i }, lineage can also be captured at the level of each task, using records and giving, for example, lineage tuples of form {(k rr, v rr ), map, (k m, v m )}.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The first form of lineage is called coarse-grain lineage, while the second form is called fine-grain lineage.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Integrating lineage across different granularities enables users to ask questions such as "Which file read by a MapReduce job produced this particular output record?" and can be useful in debugging across different operators and data granularities within a dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] To capture end-to-end lineage in a DISC system, we use the Ibis model, which introduces the notion of containment hierarchies for operators and data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Specifically, Ibis proposes that an operator can be contained within another and such a relationship between two operators is called *operator containment*.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Operator containment implies that the contained (or child) operator performs a part of the logical operation of the containing (or parent) operator.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] For example, a MapReduce task is contained in a job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Similar containment relationships exist for data as well, Known as data containment.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data containment implies that the contained data is a subset of the containing data (superset).
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Data lineage systems can be categorized as either eager or lazy.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Eager collection systems capture the entire lineage of the data flow at run time.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The kind of lineage they capture may be coarse-grain or fine-grain, but they do not require any further computations on the data flow after its execution.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lazy lineage collection typically captures only coarse-grain lineage at run time.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] These systems incur low capture overheads due to the small amount of lineage they capture.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, to answer fine-grain tracing queries, they must replay the data flow on all (or a large part) of its input and collect fine-grain lineage during the replay.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This approach is suitable for forensic systems, where a user wants to debug an observed bad output.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Eager fine-grain lineage collection systems incur higher capture overheads than lazy collection systems.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, they enable sophisticated replay and debugging.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] An actor is an entity that transforms data; it may be a Dryad vertex, individual map and reduce operators, a MapReduce job, or an entire dataflow pipeline.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Actors act as black boxes and the inputs and outputs of an actor are tapped to capture lineage in the form of associations, where an association is a triplet $\{i,T,o\}$ that relates an input i with an output o for an actor T .
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The instrumentation thus captures lineage in a dataflow one actor at a time, piecing it into a set of associations for each actor.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The system developer needs to capture the data an actor reads (from other actors) and the data an actor writes (to other actors).
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] For example, a developer can treat the Hadoop Job Tracker as an actor by recording the set of files read and written by each job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Association is a combination of the inputs, outputs and the operation itself.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The operation is represented in terms of a black box also known as the actor.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The associations describe the transformations that are applied to the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The associations are stored in the association tables.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Each unique actor is represented by its association table.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] An association itself looks like {i, T, o} where i is the set of inputs to the actor T and o is the set of outputs produced by the actor.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Associations are the basic units of Data Lineage.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Individual associations are later clubbed together to construct the entire history of transformations that were applied to the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Big data systems increase capacity by adding new hardware or software entities into the distributed system.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This process is called *horizontal scaling*.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The distributed system acts as a single entity at the logical level even though it comprises multiple hardware and software entities.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The system should continue to maintain this property after horizontal scaling.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] An important advantage of horizontal scalability is that it can provide the ability to increase capacity on the fly.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The biggest plus point is that horizontal scaling can be done using commodity hardware.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The horizontal scaling feature of Big Data systems should be taken into account while creating the architecture of lineage store.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This is essential because the lineage store itself should also be able to scale in parallel with the Big Data system.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The number of associations and amount of storage required to store lineage will increase with the increase in size and capacity of the system.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The architecture of Big Data systems makes use of a single lineage store not appropriate and impossible to scale.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The immediate solution to this problem is to distribute the lineage store itself.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The best-case scenario is to use a local lineage store for every machine in the distributed system network.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This allows the lineage store also to scale horizontally.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In this design, the lineage of data transformations applied to the data on a particular machine is stored on the local lineage store of that specific machine.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The lineage store typically stores association tables.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Each actor is represented by its own association table.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The rows are the associations themselves, and the columns represent inputs and outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] It allows horizontal scaling of the lineage store.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] If a single centralized lineage store was used, then this information had to be carried over the network, which would cause additional network latency.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The network latency is also avoided by the use of a distributed lineage store.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The information stored in terms of associations needs to be combined by some means to get the data flow of a particular job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In a distributed system a job is broken down into multiple tasks.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] One or more instances run a particular task.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The results produced on these individual machines are later combined to finish the job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Tasks running on different machines perform multiple transformations on the data in the machine.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] All the transformations applied to the data on a machine is stored in the local lineage store of that machines.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This information needs to be combined to get the lineage of the entire job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The lineage of the entire job should help the data scientist understand the data flow of the job and he/she can use the data flow to debug the Big Data pipeline.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The data flow is reconstructed in 3 stages.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The first stage of the data flow reconstruction is the computation of the association tables.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The association tables exist for each actor in each local lineage store.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The entire association table for an actor can be computed by combining these individual association tables.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This is generally done using a series of equality joins based on the actors themselves.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In few scenarios the tables might also be joined using inputs as the key.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Indexes can also be used to improve the efficiency of a join.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The joined tables need to be stored on a single instance or a machine to further continue processing.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] There are multiple schemes that are used to pick a machine where a join would be computed.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The easiest one being the one with minimum CPU load.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Space constraints should also be kept in mind while picking the instance where join would happen.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The second step in data flow reconstruction is computing an association graph from the lineage information.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The graph represents the steps in the data flow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The actors act as vertices and the associations act as edges.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Each actor T is linked to its upstream and downstream actors in the data flow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] An upstream actor of T is one that produced the input of T, while a downstream actor is one that consumes the output of T.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Containment relationships are always considered while creating the links.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The graph consists of three types of links or edges.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The simplest link is an explicitly specified link between two actors.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] These links are explicitly specified in the code of a machine learning algorithm.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] When an actor is aware of its exact upstream or downstream actor, it can communicate this information to lineage API.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This information is later used to link these actors during the tracing query.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, each map instance knows the exact record reader instance whose output it consumes.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Developers can attach data flow archetypes to each logical actor.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A data flow archetype explains how the child types of an actor type arrange themselves in a data flow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] With the help of this information, one can infer a link between each actor of a source type and a destination type.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, the map actor type is the source for reduce, and vice versa.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The system infers this from the data flow archetypes and duly links map instances with reduce instances.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, there may be several MapReduce jobs in the data flow and linking all map instances with all reduce instances can create false links.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] To prevent this, such links are restricted to actor instances contained within a common actor instance of a containing (or parent) actor type.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, map and reduce instances are only linked to each other if they belong to the same job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In distributed systems, sometimes there are implicit links, which are not specified during execution.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] For example, an implicit link exists between an actor that wrote to a file and another actor that read from it.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Such links connect actors which use a common data set for execution.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The dataset is the output of the first actor and the input of the actor follows it.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The final step in the data flow reconstruction is the topological sorting of the association graph.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The directed graph created in the previous step is topologically sorted to obtain the order in which the actors have modified the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This record of modifications by the different actors involved is used to track the data flow of the Big Data pipeline or task.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This is the most crucial step in Big Data debugging.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The captured lineage is combined and processed to obtain the data flow of the pipeline.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The data flow helps the data scientist or a developer to look deeply into the actors and their transformations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This step allows the data scientist to figure out the part of the algorithm that is generating the unexpected output.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A Big Data pipeline can go wrong in two broad ways.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The first is a presence of a suspicious actor in the dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The second is the existence of outliers in the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The first case can be debugged by tracing the dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] By using lineage and data-flow information together a data scientist can figure out how the inputs are converted into outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] During the process actors that behave unexpectedly can be caught.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Either these actors can be removed from the data flow, or they can be augmented by new actors to change the dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The improved dataflow can be replayed to test the validity of it.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Debugging faulty actors include recursively performing coarse-grain replay on actors in the dataflow, which can be expensive in resources for long dataflows.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Another approach is to manually inspect lineage logs to find anomalies, which can be tedious and time-consuming across several stages of a dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Furthermore, these approaches work only when the data scientist can discover bad outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] To debug analytics without known bad outputs, the data scientist needs to analyze the dataflow for suspicious behavior in general.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, often, a user may not know the expected normal behavior and cannot specify predicates.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This section describes a debugging methodology for retrospectively analyzing lineage to identify faulty actors in a multi-stage dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] We believe that sudden changes in an actor's behavior, such as its average selectivity, processing rate or output size, is characteristic of an anomaly.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lineage can reflect such changes in actor behavior over time and across different actor instances.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, mining lineage to identify such changes can be useful in debugging faulty actors in a dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The second problem i.e. the existence of outliers can also be identified by running the dataflow step wise and looking at the transformed outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The data scientist finds a subset of outputs that are not in accordance with the rest of outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The inputs which are causing these bad outputs are outliers in the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This problem can be solved by removing the set of outliers from the data and replaying the entire dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] It can also be solved by modifying the machine learning algorithm by adding, removing or moving actors in the dataflow.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The changes in the dataflow are successful if the replayed dataflow does not produce bad outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Although the utilization of data lineage methodologies represents a novel approach to the debugging of Big Data pipelines, the process is not straightforward.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A number of challenges must be addressed, including the scalability of the lineage store, the fault tolerance of the lineage store, the accurate capture of lineage for black box operators, and numerous other considerations.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] These challenges must be carefully evaluated in order to develop a realistic design for data lineage capture, taking into account the inherent trade-offs between them.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] DISC systems are primarily batch processing systems designed for high throughput.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] They execute several jobs per analytics, with several tasks per job.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The overall number of operators executing at any time in a cluster can range from hundreds to thousands depending on the cluster size.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lineage capture for these systems must be able scale to both large volumes of data and numerous operators to avoid being a bottleneck for the DISC analytics.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lineage capture systems must also be fault tolerant to avoid rerunning data flows to capture lineage.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] At the same time, they must also accommodate failures in the DISC system.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] To do so, they must be able to identify a failed DISC task and avoid storing duplicate copies of lineage between the partial lineage generated by the failed task and duplicate lineage produced by the restarted task.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] A lineage system should also be able to gracefully handle multiple instances of local lineage systems going down.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This can be achieved by storing replicas of lineage associations in multiple machines.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] The replica can act like a backup in the event of the real copy being lost.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lineage systems for DISC dataflows must be able to capture accurate lineage across black-box operators to enable fine-grain debugging.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Although producing highly accurate lineage, such techniques can incur significant time overheads for capture or tracing, and it may be preferable to instead trade some accuracy for better performance.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage collection system for DISC dataflows that can capture lineage from arbitrary operators with reasonable accuracy, and without significant overheads in capture or tracing.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Tracing is essential for debugging, during which a user can issue multiple tracing queries.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, it is important that tracing has fast turnaround times.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. can perform efficient backward tracing queries for MapReduce dataflows but are not generic to different DISC systems and do not perform efficient forward queries.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Lipstick, a lineage system for Pig, while able to perform both backward and forward tracing, is specific to Pig and SQL operators and can only perform coarse-grain tracing for black-box operators.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that enables efficient forward and backward tracing for generic DISC systems and dataflows with black-box operators.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Replaying only specific inputs or portions of dataflow is crucial for efficient debugging and simulating what-if scenarios.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. present a methodology for a lineage-based refresh, which selectively replays updated inputs to recompute affected outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] This is useful during debugging for re-computing outputs when a bad input has been fixed.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] However, sometimes a user may want to remove the bad input and replay the lineage of outputs previously affected by the error to produce error-free outputs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Another use of replay in debugging involves replaying bad inputs for stepwise debugging (called selective replay).
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Current approaches to using lineage in DISC systems do not address these.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that can perform both exclusive and selective replays to address different debugging needs.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] One of the primary debugging concerns in DISC systems is identifying faulty operators.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] In long dataflows with several hundreds of operators or tasks, manual inspection can be tedious and prohibitive.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] Even if lineage is used to narrow the subset of operators to examine, the lineage of a single output can still span several operators.
[src:data-catalog/data-lineage] There is a need for an inexpensive automated debugging system, which can substantially narrow the set of potentially faulty operators, with reasonable accuracy, to minimize the amount of manual examination required.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] People's views on data quality can often be in disagreement, even when discussing the same set of data used for the same purpose.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] When this is the case, businesses may adopt recognised international standards for data quality (See #International Standards for Data Quality below).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Data governance can also be used to form agreed upon definitions and standards, including international standards, for data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In such cases, data cleansing, including standardization, may be required in order to ensure data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Defining data quality is difficult due to the many contexts data are used in, as well as the varying perspectives among end users, producers, and custodians of data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] A systematic scoping review of the literature suggests that data quality dimensions and methods with real world data are not consistent in the literature, and as a result quality assessments are challenging due to the complex and heterogeneous nature of these data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] ISO 8000 is an international standard for data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Before the rise of the inexpensive computer data storage, massive mainframe computers were used to maintain name and address data for delivery services.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This was so that mail could be properly routed to its destination.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The mainframes used business rules to correct common misspellings and typographical errors in name and address data, as well as to track customers who had moved, died, gone to prison, married, divorced, or experienced other life-changing events.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Government agencies began to make postal data available to a few service companies to cross-reference customer data with the National Change of Address registry (NCOA).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This technology saved large companies millions of dollars in comparison to manual correction of customer data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Large companies saved on postage, as bills and direct marketing materials made their way to the intended customer more accurately.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Initially sold as a service, data quality moved inside the walls of corporations, as low-cost and powerful server technology became available.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Companies with an emphasis on marketing often focused their quality efforts on name and address information, but data quality is recognized as an important property of all types of data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Principles of data quality can be applied to supply chain data, transactional data, and nearly every other category of data found.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] For companies with significant research efforts, data quality can include developing protocols for research methods, reducing measurement error, bounds checking of data, cross tabulation, modeling and outlier detection, verifying data integrity, etc.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] There are a number of theoretical frameworks for understanding data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] A systems-theoretical approach influenced by American pragmatism expands the definition of data quality to include information quality, and emphasizes the inclusiveness of the fundamental dimensions of accuracy and precision on the basis of the theory of science (Ivanov, 1972).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] One framework, dubbed "Zero Defect Data" (Hansen, 1991) adapts the principles of statistical process control to data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Another framework seeks to integrate the product perspective (conformance to specifications) and the service perspective (meeting consumers' expectations) (Kahn et al.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Another framework is based in semiotics to evaluate the quality of the form, meaning and use of the data (Price and Shanks, 2004).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] One highly theoretical approach analyzes the ontological nature of information systems to define data quality rigorously (Wand and Wang, 1996).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] A considerable amount of data quality research involves investigating and describing various categories of desirable attributes (or dimensions) of data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Nearly 200 such terms have been identified and there is little agreement in their nature (are these concepts, goals or criteria?), their definitions or measures (Wang et al., 1993).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Software engineers may recognize this as a similar problem to "ilities".
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] MIT has an Information Quality (MITIQ) Program, led by Professor Richard Wang, which produces a large number of publications and hosts a significant international conference in this field (International Conference on Information Quality, ICIQ).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This program grew out of the work done by Hansen on the "Zero Defect Data" framework (Hansen, 1991).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In practice, data quality is a concern for professionals involved with a wide range of information systems, ranging from data warehousing and business intelligence to customer relationship management and supply chain management.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] One industry study estimated the total cost to the U.S. economy of data quality problems at over U.S. $600 billion per annum (Eckerson, 2002).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Incorrect data – which includes invalid and outdated information – can originate from different data sources – through data entry, or data migration and conversion projects.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In 2002, the USPS and PricewaterhouseCoopers released a report stating that 23.6 percent of all U.S. mail sent is incorrectly addressed.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] One reason contact data becomes stale very quickly in the average database – more than 45 million Americans change their address every year.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In fact, the problem is such a concern that companies are beginning to set up a data governance team whose sole role in the corporation is to be responsible for data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In some organizations, this data governance function has been established as part of a larger Regulatory Compliance function - a recognition of the importance of Data/Information Quality to organizations.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Problems with data quality don't only arise from *incorrect* data; *inconsistent* data is a problem as well.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Eliminating data shadow systems and centralizing data in a warehouse is one of the initiatives a company can take to ensure data consistency.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Enterprises, scientists, and researchers are starting to participate within data curation communities to improve the quality of their common data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The market is going some way to providing data quality assurance.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] A number of vendors make tools for analyzing and repairing poor quality data *in situ*, service providers can clean the data on a contract basis and consultants can advise on fixing processes or systems to avoid data quality problems in the first place.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Matching or Linking - a way to compare data so that similar, but slightly different records can be aligned.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Matching may use "fuzzy logic" to find duplicates in the data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] It often recognizes that "Bob" and "Bbo" may be the same individual.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] It might be able to manage "householding", or finding links between spouses at the same address, for example.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Finally, it often can build a "best of breed" record, taking the best components from multiple data sources and building a single super-record.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Monitoring - keeping track of data quality over time and reporting variations in the quality of data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Software can also auto-correct the variations based on pre-defined business rules.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Batch and Real time - Once the data is initially cleansed (batch), companies often want to build the processes into enterprise applications to keep it clean.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Data quality assurance is the process of data profiling to discover inconsistencies and other anomalies in the data, as well as performing data cleansing activities (e.g. removing outliers, missing data interpolation) to improve the data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] These activities can be undertaken as part of data warehousing or as part of the database administration of an existing piece of application software.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The Data QC process uses the information from the QA process to decide to use the data for analysis or in an application or business process.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] General example: if a Data QC process finds that the data contains too many errors or inconsistencies, then it prevents that data from being used for its intended process which could cause disruption.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Specific example: providing invalid measurements from several sensors to the automatic pilot feature on an aircraft could cause it to crash.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Thus, establishing a QC process provides data usage protection.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Data Quality (DQ) is a niche area required for the integrity of the data management by covering gaps of data issues.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This is one of the key functions that aid data governance by monitoring data to find exceptions undiscovered by current data management operations.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Data Quality checks may be defined at attribute level to have full control on its remediation steps.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] DQ checks and business rules may easily overlap if an organization is not attentive of its DQ scope.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Business teams should understand the DQ scope thoroughly in order to avoid overlap.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Data quality checks are redundant if **business logic** covers the same functionality and fulfills the same purpose as DQ.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The DQ scope of an organization should be defined in DQ strategy and well implemented.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Some data quality checks may be translated into business rules after repeated instances of exceptions in the past.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] All data having attributes referring to *Reference Data* in the organization may be validated against the set of well-defined valid values of Reference Data to discover new or discrepant values through the **validity** DQ check.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Results may be used to update *Reference Data* administered under *Master Data Management (MDM)*.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] All data sourced from a *third party* to organization's internal teams may undergo **accuracy** (DQ) check against the third party data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] These DQ check results are valuable when administered on data that made multiple hops after the point of entry of that data but before that data becomes authorized or stored for enterprise intelligence.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] All data columns that refer to *Master Data* may be validated for its **consistency** check.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] A DQ check administered on the data at the point of entry discovers new data for the MDM process, but a DQ check administered after the point of entry discovers the failure (not exceptions) of consistency.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] As data transforms, multiple timestamps and the positions of that timestamps are captured and may be compared against each other and its leeway to validate its value, decay, operational significance against a defined SLA (service level agreement).
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This **timeliness** DQ check can be utilized to decrease data value decay rate and optimize the policies of data movement timeline.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In an organization complex logic is usually segregated into simpler logic across multiple processes.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This check may be a simple generic aggregation rule engulfed by large chunk of data or it can be a complicated logic on a group of attributes of a transaction pertaining to the core business of the organization.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This DQ check requires high degree of business knowledge and acumen.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Discovery of reasonableness issues may aid for policy and strategy changes by either business or data governance or both.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] There are many places in the data movement where DQ checks may not be required.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] For instance, DQ check for completeness and precision on not–null columns is redundant for the data sourced from database.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Similarly, data should be validated for its accuracy with respect to time when the data is stitched across disparate sources.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] However, that is a business rule and should not be in the DQ scope.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Regretfully, from a software development perspective, DQ is often seen as a nonfunctional requirement.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] And as such, key data quality checks/processes are not factored into the final software solution.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Within healthcare, wearable technologies or Body Area Networks, generate large volumes of data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The level of detail required to ensure data quality is extremely high and is often underestimated.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] This is also true for the vast majority of mHealth apps, EHRs and other health related software solutions.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] However, some open source tools exist that examine data quality.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The primary reason for this, stems from the extra cost involved is added a higher degree of rigor within the software architecture.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The use of mobile devices in health, or mHealth, creates new challenges to health data security and privacy, in ways that directly affect data quality. mHealth is an increasingly important strategy for delivery of health services in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Mobile phones and tablets are used for collection, reporting, and analysis of data in near real time.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] However, these mobile devices are commonly used for personal activities, as well, leaving them more vulnerable to security risks that could lead to data breaches.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Without proper security safeguards, this personal use could jeopardize the quality, security, and confidentiality of health data.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Data quality has become a major focus of public health programs in recent years, especially as demand for accountability increases.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Work towards ambitious goals related to the fight against diseases such as AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria must be predicated on strong Monitoring and Evaluation systems that produce quality data related to program implementation.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] These programs, and program auditors, increasingly seek tools to standardize and streamline the process of determining the quality of data, verify the quality of reported data, and assess the underlying data management and reporting systems for indicators.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] An example is WHO and MEASURE Evaluation's Data Quality Review Tool WHO, the Global Fund, GAVI, and MEASURE Evaluation have collaborated to produce a harmonized approach to data quality assurance across different diseases and programs.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] There are a number of scientific works devoted to the analysis of the data quality in open data sources, such as Wikipedia, Wikidata, DBpedia and other.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] In the case of Wikipedia, quality analysis may relate to the whole article Modeling of quality there is carried out by means of various methods.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Some of them use machine learning algorithms, including Random Forest, Support Vector Machine, and others.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] Methods for assessing data quality in Wikidata, DBpedia and other LOD sources differ.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The Electronic Commerce Code Management Association (ECCMA) is a member-based, international not-for-profit association committed to improving data quality through the implementation of international standards.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] ECCMA is the current project leader for the development of ISO 8000 and ISO 22745, which are the international standards for data quality and the exchange of material and service master data, respectively.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] ECCMA provides a platform for collaboration amongst subject experts on data quality and data governance around the world to build and maintain global, open standard dictionaries that are used to unambiguously label information.
[src:data-catalog/data-quality] The existence of these dictionaries (known as Open Technical Dictionaries) of labels (acting as metadata and reference data) allows information to be passed from one computer system to another without losing meaning.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] As such, efforts to define, classify types, or structure metadata are expressed as examples in the context of its use.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" has a history dating to the 1960s where it occurred in computer science and in popular culture.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Different types of metadata serve different functions.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, descriptive metadata for a document might include the author, creation date, file size and keywords.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] It can help users find relevant information and discover resources.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] It can also help organize electronic resources, provide digital identification, and archive and preserve resources.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata allows users to access resources by "allowing resources to be found by relevant criteria, identifying resources, bringing similar resources together, distinguishing dissimilar resources, and giving location information".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata of telecommunication activities including Internet traffic is very widely collected by various national governmental organizations.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This data is used for the purposes of traffic analysis and can be used for mass surveillance.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Unique metadata standards exist for different disciplines (e.g., museum collections, digital audio files, websites, etc.).
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Describing the contents and context of data or data files increases its usefulness.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, a web page may include metadata specifying what software language the page is written in (e.g., HTML), what tools were used to create it, what subjects the page is about, and where to find more information about the subject.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This metadata can automatically improve the reader's experience and make it easier for users to find the web page online.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A CD may include metadata providing information about the musicians, singers, and songwriters whose work appears on the disc.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] In many countries, government organizations routinely store metadata about emails, telephone calls, web pages, video traffic, IP connections, and cell phone locations.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata is not strictly bound to one of these categories, as it can describe a piece of data in many other ways.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] While the metadata application is manifold, covering a large variety of fields, there are specialized and well-accepted models to specify types of metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Bretherton & Singley (1994) distinguish between two distinct classes: structural/control metadata and guide metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes the structure of database objects such as tables, columns, keys and indexes.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] *Guide metadata* helps humans find specific items and is usually expressed as a set of keywords in a natural language.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] According to Ralph Kimball, metadata can be divided into three categories: *technical metadata* (or internal metadata), *business metadata* (or external metadata), and *process metadata*.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Business metadata is important because it can greatly facilitate the usefulness of the data to business people.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A simple example of business metadata is a glossary entry.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Hover functionality in an application or web form can enable a glossary definition to be shown when cursor is on a field or term.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Other examples of business metadata include annotation ability within applications.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, a business user may be viewing a business intelligence (BI) report and notice a trend in the data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The user may have background knowledge as to why this trend occurs.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Some business intelligence tools enable the user to create an annotation within the report that explains the trend.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Such an annotation can enhance other users' understanding of the data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This example is especially powerful because it is created by a business user for the use of other business people.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] NISO distinguishes three types of metadata: descriptive, structural, and administrative.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] *Descriptive metadata* is typically used for discovery and identification, as information to search and locate an object, such as title, authors, subjects, keywords, and publisher.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes how the components of an object are organized.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] An example of structural metadata would be how pages are ordered to form chapters of a book.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Finally, *administrative metadata* gives information to help manage the source.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Administrative metadata refers to the technical information, such as file type, or when and how the file was created.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Two sub-types of administrative metadata are rights management metadata and preservation metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] *Rights management metadata* explains intellectual property rights, while *preservation metadata* contains information to preserve and save a resource.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] An additional type of metadata beginning to be more developed is *accessibility metadata*.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Accessibility metadata is not a new concept to libraries; however, advances in universal design have raised its profile.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Projects like Cloud4All and GPII identified the lack of common terminologies and models to describe the needs and preferences of users and information that fits those needs as a major gap in providing universal access solutions.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Those types of information are accessibility metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The Schema.org website has incorporated several accessibility properties based on IMS Global Access for All Information Model Data Element Specification.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] While the efforts to describe and standardize the varied accessibility needs of information seekers are beginning to become more robust, their adoption into established metadata schemas has not been as developed.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, while Dublin Core (DC)'s "audience" and MARC 21's "reading level" could be used to identify resources suitable for users with dyslexia and DC's "format" could be used to identify resources available in braille, audio, or large print formats, there is more work to be done.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata was traditionally used in the card catalogs of libraries until the 1980s when libraries converted their catalog data to digital databases.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] In the 2000s, as data and information were increasingly stored digitally, this digital data was described using metadata standards.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] An early description of "meta data" for computer systems was written by David Griffel and Stuart McIntosh at the MIT Center for International Studies in 1967: "In summary then, we have statements in an object language about subject descriptions of data and token codes for the data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata is defined as the data providing information about one or more aspects of the data; it is used to summarize basic information about data that can make tracking and working with specific data easier.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, a digital image may include metadata that describes the size of the image, its color depth, resolution, when it was created, the shutter speed, and other data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A text document's metadata may contain information about how long the document is, who the author is, when the document was written, and a short summary of the document.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata within web pages can also contain descriptions of page content, as well as key words linked to the content.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] These links are often called "Metatags", which were used as the primary factor in determining order for a web search until the late 1990s.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The reliance on metatags in web searches was decreased in the late 1990s because of "keyword stuffing", whereby metatags were being largely misused to trick search engines into thinking some websites had more relevance in the search than they really did.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata can be stored and managed in a database, often called a metadata registry or metadata repository.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] However, without context and a point of reference, it might be impossible to identify metadata just by looking at it.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example: by itself, a database containing several numbers, all 13 digits long could be the results of calculations or a list of numbers to plug into an equation – without any other context, the numbers themselves can be perceived as the data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] But if given the context that this database is a log of a book collection, those 13-digit numbers may now be identified as ISBNs – information that refers to the book, but is not itself the information within the book.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" was coined in 1968 by Philip Bagley, in his book "Extension of Programming Language Concepts" where it is clear that he uses the term in the ISO 11179 "traditional" sense, which is "structural metadata" i.e.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] "data about the containers of data"; rather than the alternative sense "content about individual instances of data content" or metacontent, the type of data usually found in library catalogs.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Since then the fields of information management, information science, information technology, librarianship, and GIS have widely adopted the term.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] In these fields, the word *metadata* is defined as "data about data".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] While this is the generally accepted definition, various disciplines have adopted their own more specific explanations and uses of the term.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) or, more correctly, the vocabularies used to assemble metadata (metacontent) statements, is typically structured according to a standardized concept using a well-defined metadata scheme, including metadata standards and metadata models.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Tools such as controlled vocabularies, taxonomies, thesauri, data dictionaries, and metadata registries can be used to apply further standardization to the metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Structural metadata commonality is also of paramount importance in data model development and in database design.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) syntax refers to the rules created to structure the fields or elements of metadata (metacontent).
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A single metadata scheme may be expressed in a number of different markup or programming languages, each of which requires a different syntax.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, Dublin Core may be expressed in plain text, HTML, XML, and RDF.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A common example of (guide) metacontent is the bibliographic classification, the subject, the Dewey Decimal class number.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] There is always an implied statement in any "classification" of some object.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] To classify an object as, for example, Dewey class number 514 (Topology) (i.e. books having the number 514 on their spine) the implied statement is: "<book><subject heading><514>".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This is a subject-predicate-object triple, or more importantly, a class-attribute-value triple.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The first 2 elements of the triple (class, attribute) are pieces of some structural metadata having a defined semantic.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The third element is a value, preferably from some controlled vocabulary, some reference (master) data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The combination of the metadata and master data elements results in a statement which is a metacontent statement i.e.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] All of these elements can be thought of as "vocabulary".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Both metadata and master data are vocabularies that can be assembled into metacontent statements.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] There are many sources of these vocabularies, both meta and master data: UML, EDIFACT, XSD, Dewey/UDC/LoC, SKOS, ISO-25964, Pantone, Linnaean Binomial Nomenclature, etc.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The process indexes pages and then matches text strings using its complex algorithm; there is no intelligence or "inferencing" occurring, just the illusion thereof.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can be hierarchical in nature where relationships exist between metadata elements and elements are nested so that parent-child relationships exist between the elements.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] An example of a hierarchical metadata schema is the IEEE LOM schema, in which metadata elements may belong to a parent metadata element.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can also be one-dimensional, or linear, where each element is completely discrete from other elements and classified according to one dimension only.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] An example of a linear metadata schema is the Dublin Core schema, which is one-dimensional.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata are often 2 dimensional, or planar, where each element is completely discrete from other elements but classified according to 2 orthogonal dimensions.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The degree to which the data or metadata is structured is referred to as "granularity".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] "Granularity" refers to how much detail is provided.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata with a high granularity allows for deeper, more detailed, and more structured information and enables a greater level of technical manipulation.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A lower level of granularity means that metadata can be created for considerably lower costs but will not provide as detailed information.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The major impact of granularity is not only on creation and capture, but moreover on maintenance costs.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] As soon as the metadata structures become outdated, so too is the access to the referred data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Hence granularity must take into account the effort to create the metadata as well as the effort to maintain it.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] In all cases where the metadata schemata exceed the planar depiction, some type of hypermapping is required to enable display and view of metadata according to chosen aspect and to serve special views.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Hypermapping frequently applies to layering of geographical and geological information overlays.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] International standards apply to metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Much work is being accomplished in the national and international standards communities, especially ANSI (American National Standards Institute) and ISO (International Organization for Standardization) to reach a consensus on standardizing metadata and registries.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The core metadata registry standard is ISO/IEC 11179 Metadata Registries (MDR), the framework for the standard is described in ISO/IEC 11179-1:2004.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] A new edition of Part 1 is in its final stage for publication in 2015 or early 2016.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] It has been revised to align with the current edition of Part 3, ISO/IEC 11179-3:2013 which extends the MDR to support the registration of Concept Systems.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This standard specifies a schema for recording both the meaning and technical structure of the data for unambiguous usage by humans and computers.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 standard refers to metadata as information objects about data, or "data about data".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] In ISO/IEC 11179 Part-3, the information objects are data about Data Elements, Value Domains, and other reusable semantic and representational information objects that describe the meaning and technical details of a data item.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This standard also prescribes the details for a metadata registry, and for registering and administering the information objects within a Metadata Registry.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 Part 3 also has provisions for describing compound structures that are derivations of other data elements, for example through calculations, collections of one or more data elements, or other forms of derived data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This standard has become the general basis for other kinds of metadata registries, reusing and extending the registration and administration portion of the standard.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The Geospatial community has a tradition of specialized geospatial metadata standards, particularly building on traditions of map- and image-libraries and catalogs.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Formal metadata is usually essential for geospatial data, as common text-processing approaches are not applicable.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The Dublin Core metadata terms are a set of vocabulary terms that can be used to describe resources for the purposes of discovery.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The W3C Data Catalog Vocabulary (DCAT) is an RDF vocabulary that supplements Dublin Core with classes for Dataset, Data Service, Catalog, and Catalog Record.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] DCAT also uses elements from FOAF, PROV-O, and OWL-Time.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] DCAT provides an RDF model to support the typical structure of a catalog that contains records, each describing a dataset or service.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Although not a standard, Microformat (also mentioned in the section metadata on the internet below) is a web-based approach to semantic markup which seeks to re-use existing HTML/XHTML tags to convey metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Microformat follows XHTML and HTML standards but is not a standard in itself.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] In metadata, Naming and Design Rules are a set of guidelines and naming conventions that go beyond what a single data exchange standard specification will permit.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] The most common standard that Naming and Design Rules are created on is XML Schema.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] For example, the use of upper camel case data element names is a convention used in many standard but is not specified by the XML Schema specification.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Naming and Design Rules have become an important aspect of each organizations data exchange standards.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Within the United States, Naming and Design Rules standards are recommended for each federal and state agency.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Most common types of computer files can embed metadata, including documents, (e.g.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Microsoft Office files, OpenDocument files, PDF) images, (e.g.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata may be added to files by users, but some metadata is often automatically added to files by authoring applications or by devices used to produce the files, without user intervention.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] While metadata in files are useful for finding them, they can be a privacy hazard when the files are shared.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Using metadata removal tools to clean files before sharing them can mitigate this risk.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Some metadata is created by the camera such as, color space, color channels, exposure time, and aperture (EXIF), while some is input by the photographer and/or software after downloading to a computer.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Most digital cameras write metadata about the model number, shutter speed, etc., and some enable you to edit it; this functionality has been available on most Nikon DSLRs since the Nikon D3, on most new Canon cameras since the Canon EOS 7D, and on most Pentax DSLRs since the Pentax K-3.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata can be used to make organizing in post-production easier with the use of key-wording.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Filters can be used to analyze a specific set of photographs and create selections on criteria like rating or capture time.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] On devices with geolocation capabilities like GPS (smartphones in particular), the location the photo was taken from may also be included.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Photographic Metadata Standards are governed by organizations that develop the following standards.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata is particularly useful in video, where information about its contents (such as transcripts of conversations and text descriptions of its scenes) is not directly understandable by a computer, but where an efficient search of the content is desirable.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] This is particularly useful in video applications such as Automatic Number Plate Recognition and Vehicle Recognition Identification software, wherein license plate data is saved and used to create reports and alerts.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Avid's MetaSync and Adobe's Bridge are examples of professional video editing software with access to metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Various file systems are utilising metadata, such as FAT32 and NTFS.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Information on the times, origins and destinations of phone calls, electronic messages, instant messages, and other modes of telecommunication, as opposed to message content, is another form of metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Geospatial metadata relates to Geographic Information Systems (GIS) files, maps, images, and other data that is location-based.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] Metadata is used in GIS to document the characteristics and attributes of geographic data, such as database files and data that is developed within a GIS.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p01] It includes details like who developed the data, when it was collected, how it was processed, and what formats it's available in, and then delivers the context for the data to be used effectively.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata can be created either by automated information processing or by manual work.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Elementary metadata captured by computers can include information about when an object was created, who created it, when it was last updated, file size, and file extension.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] A metadata engine collects, stores and analyzes information about data and metadata in use within a domain.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Data virtualization emerged in the 2000s as the new software technology to complete the virtualization "stack" in the enterprise.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata is used in data virtualization servers which are enterprise infrastructure components, alongside database and application servers.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata in these servers is saved as persistent repository and describe business objects in various enterprise systems and applications.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Structural metadata commonality is also important to support data virtualization.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Standardization and harmonization work has brought advantages to industry efforts to build metadata systems in the statistical community.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Several metadata guidelines and standards such as the European Statistics Code of Practice and ISO 17369:2013 (Statistical Data and Metadata Exchange or SDMX) provide key principles for how businesses, government bodies, and other entities should manage statistical data and metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Entities such as Eurostat, European System of Central Banks, and the U.S.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Environmental Protection Agency have implemented these and other such standards and guidelines with the goal of improving "efficiency when managing statistical business processes".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata has been used in various ways as a means of cataloging items in libraries in both digital and analog formats.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Such data helps classify, aggregate, identify, and locate a particular book, DVD, magazine, or any object a library might hold in its collection.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Until the 1980s, many library catalogs used 3x5 inch cards in file drawers to display a book's title, author, subject matter, and an abbreviated alpha-numeric string (call number) which indicated the physical location of the book within the library's shelves.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The Dewey Decimal System employed by libraries for the classification of library materials by subject is an early example of metadata usage.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The early paper catalog had information regarding whichever item was described on said card: title, author, subject, and a number as to where to find said item.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Beginning in the 1980s and 1990s, many libraries replaced these paper file cards with computer databases.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] These computer databases make it much easier and faster for users to do keyword searches.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Another form of older metadata collection is the use by the US Census Bureau of what is known as the "Long Form".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The Long Form asks questions that are used to create demographic data to find patterns of distribution.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Libraries employ metadata in library catalogues, most commonly as part of an Integrated Library Management System.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata is obtained by cataloging resources such as books, periodicals, DVDs, web pages or digital images.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This data is stored in the integrated library management system, ILMS, using the MARC metadata standard.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The purpose is to direct patrons to the physical or electronic location of items or areas they seek as well as to provide a description of the item/s in question.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] More recent and specialized instances of library metadata include the establishment of digital libraries including e-print repositories and digital image libraries.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] While often based on library principles, the focus on non-librarian use, especially in providing metadata, means they do not follow traditional or common cataloging approaches.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Given the custom nature of included materials, metadata fields are often specially created e.g. taxonomic classification fields, location fields, keywords, or copyright statement.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Standard file information such as file size and format are usually automatically included.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Library operation has for decades been a key topic in efforts toward international standardization.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Standards for metadata in digital libraries include Dublin Core, METS, MODS, DDI, DOI, URN, PREMIS schema, EML, and OAI-PMH.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Leading libraries in the world give hints on their metadata standards strategies.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] A similar concept is the synset, short for *synonym set*, a group of one or more synonyms that share a common meaning in some context.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Synsets are a fundamental concept in computational linguistics and lexical semantics, most notably used in the WordNet lexical database of English.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The concept has been extended to other languages and multilingual projects such as EuroWordNet, BabelNet, and the Global WordNet initiative.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata for scientific publications is often created by journal publishers and citation databases such as PubMed and Web of Science.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The data contained within manuscripts or accompanying them as supplementary material is less often subject to metadata creation, though they may be submitted to e.g. biomedical databases after publication.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The original authors and database curators then become responsible for metadata creation, with the assistance of automated processes.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Comprehensive metadata for all experimental data is the foundation of the FAIR Guiding Principles, or the standards for ensuring research data are findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Such metadata can then be utilized, complemented, and made accessible in useful ways.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] OpenAlex is a free online index of over 200 million scientific documents that integrates and provides metadata such as sources, citations, author information, scientific fields, and research topics.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Its API and open source website can be used for metascience, scientometrics, and novel tools that query this semantic web of papers.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Another project under development, Scholia, uses the metadata of scientific publications for various visualizations and aggregation features such as providing a simple user interface summarizing literature about a specific feature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus using Wikidata's "main subject" property.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In research labor, transparent metadata about authors' contributions to works have been proposed – e.g. the role played in the production of the paper, the level of contribution and the responsibilities.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Moreover, various metadata about scientific outputs can be created or complemented – for instance, some organizations attempt to track and link citations of papers as 'Supporting', 'Mentioning' or 'Contrasting' the study.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata in a museum context is the information that trained cultural documentation specialists, such as archivists, librarians, museum registrars and curators, create to index, structure, describe, identify, or otherwise specify works of art, architecture, cultural objects and their images.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Descriptive metadata is most commonly used in museum contexts for object identification and resource recovery purposes.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Many museums and cultural heritage centers recognize that given the diversity of artworks and cultural objects, no single model or standard suffices to describe and catalog cultural works.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] For example, a sculpted Indigenous artifact could be classified as an artwork, an archaeological artifact, or an Indigenous heritage item.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] These standards use HTML and XML markup languages for machine processing, publication and implementation.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules (AACR), originally developed for characterizing books, have also been applied to cultural objects, works of art and architecture.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Standards, such as the CCO, are integrated within a Museum's Collections Management System (CMS), a database through which museums are able to manage their collections, acquisitions, loans and conservation.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Scholars and professionals in the field note that the "quickly evolving landscape of standards and technologies" creates challenges for cultural documentarians, specifically non-technically trained professionals.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Most collecting institutions and museums use a relational database to categorize cultural works and their images.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Relational databases and metadata work to document and describe the complex relationships amongst cultural objects and multi-faceted works of art, as well as between objects and places, people, and artistic movements.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Relational database structures are also beneficial within collecting institutions and museums because they allow for archivists to make a clear distinction between cultural objects and their images; an unclear distinction could lead to confusing and inaccurate searches.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The established institutional cataloging practices, goals, and expertise of cultural documentarians and database structure also influence the information ascribed to cultural objects and the ways in which cultural objects are categorized.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Additionally, museums often employ standardized commercial collection management software that prescribes and limits the ways in which archivists can describe artworks and cultural objects.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] As well, collecting institutions and museums use Controlled Vocabularies to describe cultural objects and artworks in their collections.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Getty Vocabularies and the Library of Congress Controlled Vocabularies are reputable within the museum community and are recommended by CCO standards.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Museums are encouraged to use controlled vocabularies that are contextual and relevant to their collections and enhance the functionality of their digital information systems.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Controlled Vocabularies are beneficial within databases because they provide a high level of consistency, improving resource retrieval.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata structures, including controlled vocabularies, reflect the ontologies of the systems from which they were created.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Often the processes through which cultural objects are described and categorized through metadata in museums do not reflect the perspectives of the maker communities.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata has been instrumental in the creation of digital information systems and archives within museums and has made it easier for museums to publish digital content online.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This has enabled audiences who might not have had access to cultural objects due to geographic or economic barriers to have access to them.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In the 2000s, as more museums have adopted archival standards and created intricate databases, discussions about Linked Data between museum databases have come up in the museum, archival, and library science communities.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Collection Management Systems (CMS) and Digital Asset Management tools can be local or shared systems.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Digital Humanities scholars note many benefits of interoperability between museum databases and collections, while also acknowledging the difficulties of achieving such interoperability.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Problems involving metadata in litigation in the United States are becoming widespread.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Courts have looked at various questions involving metadata, including the discoverability of metadata by parties.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The Federal Rules of Civil Procedure have specific rules for discovery of electronically stored information, and subsequent case law applying those rules has elucidated on the litigant's duty to produce metadata when litigating in federal court.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In October 2009, the Arizona Supreme Court has ruled that metadata records are public record.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Document metadata have proven particularly important in legal environments in which litigation has requested metadata, that can include sensitive information detrimental to a certain party in court.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Using metadata removal tools to "clean" or redact documents can mitigate the risks of unwittingly sending sensitive data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This process partially (see data remanence) protects law firms from potentially damaging leaking of sensitive data through electronic discovery.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Opinion polls have shown that 45% of Americans are "not at all confident" in the ability of social media sites to ensure their personal data is secure and 40% say that social media sites should not be able to store any information on individuals.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] 76% of Americans say that they are not confident that the information advertising agencies collect on them is secure and 50% say that online advertising agencies should not be allowed to record any of their information at all.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In the EU, the Snowden disclosures have been influential in its review of matters concerning privacy and the processing of personal data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] As of 2025, of the 18 European countries surveyed by the Data Retention Directive, only Germany, the Netherlands and Romania do not have any data retention rules in force.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] On 6 October 2020, the Court of Justice for the European Union (CJEU) ruled that indiscriminate mass data retention schemes are illegal under EU law.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] With France passing a law on 18 December 2013 that facilitates the collection of data by the French military and intelligence services.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] While in April 2022 the Portuguese Constitutional Court declared unconstitutional the CJEU laws on the retention of data generated or processed in connection with the provision of publicly available electronic communications services or of public communications networks.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In Australia, the need to strengthen national security has resulted in the introduction of a new metadata storage law.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This new law means that both security and policing agencies will be allowed to access up to 2 years of an individual's metadata, with the aim of making it easier to stop any terrorist attacks and serious crimes from happening.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Legislative metadata has been discussed in various forums, such as workshops held by the Legal Information Institute at the Cornell Law School on 22 and 23 March 2010.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The documentation for these workshops is titled "Suggested metadata practices for legislation and regulations".
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Australian medical research pioneered the definition of metadata for applications in health care.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] That approach offers the first recognized attempt to adhere to international standards in medical sciences instead of defining a proprietary standard under the World Health Organization (WHO) umbrella.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The medical community yet did not approve of the need to follow metadata standards despite research that supported these standards.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Research studies in the fields of biomedicine and molecular biology frequently yield large quantities of data, including results of genome or meta-genome sequencing, proteomics data, and even notes or plans created during the course of research itself.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Each data type involves its own variety of metadata and the processes necessary to produce these metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] General metadata standards, such as ISA-Tab, allow researchers to create and exchange experimental metadata in consistent formats.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Specific experimental approaches frequently have their own metadata standards and systems: metadata standards for mass spectrometry include mzML and SPLASH, while XML-based standards such as PDBML and SRA XML serve as standards for macromolecular structure and sequencing data, respectively.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The products of biomedical research are generally realized as peer-reviewed manuscripts and these publications are yet another source of data .
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] A data warehouse (DW) is a repository of an organization's electronically stored data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Data warehouses are designed to manage and store the data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Data warehouses differ from business intelligence (BI) systems because BI systems are designed to use data to create reports and analyze the information, to provide strategic guidance to management.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata is an important tool in how data is stored in data warehouses.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The purpose of a data warehouse is to house standardized, structured, consistent, integrated, correct, "cleaned" and timely data, extracted from various operational systems in an organization.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The extracted data are integrated in the data warehouse environment to provide an enterprise-wide perspective.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Data are structured in a way to serve the reporting and analytic requirements.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The design of structural metadata commonality using a data modeling method such as entity-relationship model diagramming is important in any data warehouse development effort.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] They detail metadata on each piece of data in the data warehouse.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] An essential component of a data warehouse/business intelligence system is the metadata and tools to manage and retrieve the metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Ralph Kimball describes metadata as the DNA of the data warehouse as metadata defines the elements of the data warehouse and how they work together.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Kimball et al. refer to three main categories of metadata: technical, business and process.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Technical metadata is primarily definitional, while business metadata and process metadata are primarily descriptive.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The HTML format used to define web pages allows for the inclusion of a variety of types of metadata, from basic descriptive text, dates and keywords to further advanced metadata schemes such as the Dublin Core, e-GMS, and AGLS standards.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Pages and files can also be geotagged with coordinates, categorized or tagged, including collaboratively such as with folksonomies.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] When media has identifiers set or when such can be generated, information such as file tags and descriptions can be pulled or scraped from the Internet – for example about movies.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Various online databases are aggregated and provide metadata for various data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The collaboratively built Wikidata has identifiers not just for media but also abstract concepts, various objects, and other entities, that can be looked up by humans and machines to retrieve useful information and to link knowledge in other knowledge bases and databases.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata may be included in the page's header or in a separate file.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Microformats allow metadata to be added to on-page data in a way that regular web users do not see, but computers, web crawlers and search engines can readily access.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Many search engines are cautious about using metadata in their ranking algorithms because of exploitation of metadata and the practice of search engine optimization, SEO, to improve rankings.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] See the Meta element article for further discussion.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This cautious attitude may be justified as people, according to Doctorow, are not executing care and diligence when creating their own metadata and that metadata is part of a competitive environment where the metadata is used to promote the metadata creators own purposes.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Studies show that search engines respond to web pages with metadata implementations, and Google has an announcement on its site showing the meta tags that its search engine understands.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Enterprise search startup Swiftype recognizes metadata as a relevance signal that webmasters can implement for their website-specific search engine, even releasing their own extension, known as Meta Tags 2.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This metadata can be linked to the video media thanks to the video servers.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Most major broadcast sporting events like FIFA World Cup or the Olympic Games use this metadata to distribute their video content to TV stations through keywords.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] It is often the host broadcaster who is in charge of organizing metadata through its *International Broadcast Centre* and its video servers.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This metadata is recorded with the images and entered by metadata operators (*loggers*) who associate in live metadata available in *metadata grids* through software (such as Multicam(LSM) or IPDirector used during the FIFA World Cup or Olympic Games).
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Ecological and environmental metadata is intended to document the "who, what, when, where, why, and how" of data collection for a particular study.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] This typically means which organization or institution collected the data, what type of data, which date(s) the data was collected, the rationale for the data collection, and the methodology used for the data collection.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata should be generated in a format commonly used by the most relevant science community, such as Darwin Core, Ecological Metadata Language, or Dublin Core.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata editing tools exist to facilitate metadata generation (e.g.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata should describe the provenance of the data (where they originated, as well as any transformations the data underwent) and how to give credit for (cite) the data products.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] When first released in 1982, Compact Discs only contained a Table Of Contents (TOC) with the number of tracks on the disc and their length in samples.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Fourteen years later in 1996, a revision of the CD Red Book standard added CD-Text to carry additional metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Shortly thereafter, it became common for personal computers to retrieve metadata from external sources (e.g.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Digital audio formats such as digital audio files superseded music formats such as cassette tapes and CDs in the 2000s.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Digital audio files could be labeled with more information than could be contained in just the file name.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] That descriptive information is called the **audio tag** or audio metadata in general.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Computer programs specializing in adding or modifying this information are called tag editors.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata can be used to name, describe, catalog, and indicate ownership or copyright for a digital audio file, and its presence makes it much easier to locate a specific audio file within a group, typically through use of a search engine that accesses the metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] As different digital audio formats were developed, attempts were made to standardize a specific location within the digital files where this information could be stored.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] As a result, almost all digital audio formats, including mp3, broadcast wav, and AIFF files, have similar standardized locations that can be populated with metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The metadata for compressed and uncompressed digital music is often encoded in the ID3 tag.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Common editors such as TagLib support MP3, Ogg Vorbis, FLAC, MPC, Speex, WavPack TrueAudio, WAV, AIFF, MP4, and ASF file formats.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] With the availability of cloud applications, which include those to add metadata to content, metadata is increasingly available over the Internet.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored either *internally*, in the same file or structure as the data (this is also called *embedded metadata*), or *externally*, in a separate file or field from the described data.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] A data repository typically stores the metadata *detached* from the data but can be designed to support embedded metadata approaches.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored in either human-readable or binary form.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Storing metadata in a human-readable format such as XML can be useful because users can understand and edit it without specialized tools.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] However, text-based formats are rarely optimized for storage capacity, communication time, or processing speed.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] A binary metadata format enables efficiency in all these respects, but requires special software to convert the binary information into human-readable content.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Each relational database system has its own mechanisms for storing metadata.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In database terminology, this set of metadata is referred to as the catalog.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the information schema, but not all databases implement it, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Programmatic access to metadata is possible using APIs such as JDBC, or SchemaCrawler.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] One of the first satirical examinations of the concept of Metadata as we understand it today is American science fiction author Hal Draper's short story, "MS Fnd in a Lbry" (1961).
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Here, the knowledge of all Mankind is condensed into an object the size of a desk drawer, however, the magnitude of the metadata (e.g. catalog of catalogs of... , as well as indexes and histories) eventually leads to dire yet humorous consequences for the human race.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] The story prefigures the modern consequences of allowing metadata to become more important than the real data it is concerned with, and the risks inherent in that eventuality as a cautionary tale.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Documentation refers to all contextual information that explains and describes a dataset, system, or research process to ensure it is understandable, usable, and reusable.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] It covers broad details such as the study background, data collection methods, file inventories, codebooks, data dictionaries, user guides, and workflow notes.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] In contrast, metadata is a specific and highly structured form of documentation that provides standardized information about the data itself—such as the title, creator, file format, size, access conditions, and how files or sections are organized.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Metadata and documentation are therefore related but distinct concepts in information management.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] Both play crucial roles in data governance, usability, and preservation.
[src:data-catalog/metadata-p02] While documentation gives the full narrative and instructions surrounding the data, metadata offers concise, structured descriptors that help users and systems identify, locate, manage and preserve the data efficiently.
